{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 7.20** (from the work *Manusmṛti* attributed to Manu) states that if a king fails to consistently impose *daṇḍa* (punishment or the rod of chastisement) on those who deserve it, the strong will devour the weak, likened to fish roasting on a spit.[^1]\n\nThis verse is part of a broader discussion in Chapter 7 on the king's duty to wield *daṇḍa* as the embodiment of Dharma (law and order). The text portrays *daṇḍa* as the Lord's son, created from Brahma's luster to protect all beings; through fear of it, creatures adhere to their duties.[^2] The king must apply it judiciously, considering time, place, ability, and scripture, or risk chaos where \"the crow would eat the sacrificial cake\" and social hierarchies collapse.[^3] Properly used, *daṇḍa* ensures prosperity; misused, it destroys the wielder.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-d56424).\n\n[^2]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 7, [verses 14–18](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-73f910).\n\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [verses 16–21](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-ab7b2a).\n\n[^4]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 7, [verses 19–22](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/07/translation/#p-6458d4).",
